<subSection id="3B502F2D313FFF8EFF60EFE7FA8A9972" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" type="multiple">
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF60EFE7FD179EA9" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" box="[151,653,389,414]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<heading id="092881AA313FFF8EFF60EFE7FD179EA9" bold="true" box="[151,653,389,414]" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" reason="2">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF60EFE7FD179EA9" bold="true" box="[151,653,389,414]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Diagnostic characters of Japanese species.</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30EFCAFD199D41" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30EFCAFE939EF5" bold="true" box="[199,265,424,450]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30EFCAFE989EF6" bold="true" box="[199,258,424,449]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Male</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFEE7EFCBFED69EF5" box="[272,332,425,450]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Head</emphasis>
. Occiput black in ground color, with gray pruinosity; prementum dark or reddish brown. Vertex 1/ 5â€“1/4 of head width; parafacial very narrow in the middle, 
<date id="26611006313FFF8EFCDEEFAFFC009ED1" box="[809,922,461,486]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" value="2017-01-25" valueMax="2017-01-01" valueMin="2017-01-25">1/25â€“1/17</date>
of head width; gena narrow, 1/13â€“1/7 of head height; ocellar triangle small, not reaching lunule; 2 frontal setae; 2 reclinate orbital setae; fronto-orbital plate without any supplemental setula; 1â€“2 supravibrissal setae; 1 vibrissa; 1â€“3 subvibrissal setulae; 1â€“2 genal setae; compound eye bare. First aristomere as long as wide; 2nd aristomere longer than wide; 3rd aristomere thickened on basal 1/5; arista plumose only on basal half.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30ECE3FB929C1D" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30ECE3FE829DAD" box="[199,280,641,666]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Thorax</emphasis>
. Two proepisternal setae, anterior one shorter than posterior; 2â€“3 proepimeral setae; 2â€“3 postpronotal setae; acrostichal seta fine; 1â€“2 presutural and 3 postsutural dorsocentral setae; 1 presutural and 1â€“3 postsutural intra-alar setae; 1 presutural and 1 postsutural supra-alar setae; 2 postalar setae; 2 notopleural setae; 4â€“6 anepisternal setae; 3 katepisternal setae, forming equilateral triangle; anepimeron, katepimeron, meron, katatergite, and anatergite bare; apical scutellar seta as long as basal one; prosternum bare.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30ED54FAF29CA2" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30ED54FF659C7A" box="[199,255,822,845]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Wing</emphasis>
. Tegula, basicosta, and all veins brown; upper and lower calypters white; halter creamy. Vein M not bending anteriorly at apical part; distance of M between crossveins r-m and dm-cu shorter than distance between crossvein dm-cu and wing margin; crossvein dm-cu nearly straight, longer than ultimate section of vein CuA1.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30EDC7FE1A9B1E" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30EDC7FF669C8B" box="[199,252,933,956]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Legs</emphasis>
. All tibiae, tarsi, and pulvilli creamy yellow; all claws brown. Fore tibia with 1 posterior, 2 preapical dorsal, and 3 apical ventral setae; mid femur with 2 preapical posterior setae; mid tibia with 2â€“3 posterodorsal, 2 preapical dorsal, and 3 apical ventral setae; hind tibia with 2 preapical dorsal and 3 apical ventral setae; pulvillus rectangular in shape.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30EA56FC1A9B7B" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" box="[199,896,1076,1101]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30EA56FEAB9B7A" box="[199,305,1076,1101]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Tergites 3â€“5 with several discal and marginal setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30EA3AFA1B9BEA" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30EA3AFE1A9B46" box="[199,384,1112,1137]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Male terminalia</emphasis>
. Tergite 6 greatly reduced or very slender; syntergosternite 7+8 small with several setae; sternite 6 slender and symmetric; epandrium semicircular and notched laterally with many setae; surstylus and cerci fused with epandrium; hypandrial arms fused and broad; pregonite small and round apically; phallus curved dorsally at middle; distiphallus broad and orbicular with large membranous areas laterally, apical part hook-like.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30EA85FBBB9A12" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30EA85FEBF9A37" bold="true" box="[199,293,1255,1280]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Female.</emphasis>
Similar to male in general appearance, differing from male by the body color, length of 1 
<taxonomicName id="95DF4D45313FFF8EFA71EA8AFEBD9A12" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="flagellomere">st flagellomere</taxonomicName>
, shape of hind leg, shape of segment 5 of abdomen, and chaetotaxy.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30EB52FB1B9A5A" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30EB52FE0C9A7E" box="[199,406,1328,1353]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Female terminalia</emphasis>
. Tergite 6, sternites 7 and 8 strongly reduced with some setulae; sternite 6 broad with setae; hemitergite 7 small and bare; hemitergite 8 narrow with some setulae at posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30EB1AFB339AEE" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFF30EB1AFEA19AA6" bold="true" box="[199,315,1400,1425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="364E4B37313FFF8EFEB5EB1AFD909AA7" box="[322,522,1400,1425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" refId="ref8449" refString="Shinonaga, S. (2003) Monograph of the Muscidae of Japan. Tokai University Press, Tokyo, 347 pp." type="book">Shinonaga (2003)</bibRefCitation>
recorded 
<taxonomicName id="95DF4D45313FFF8EFD8CEB1AFB9B9AA6" authority="Karl, 1935" authorityName="Karl" authorityYear="1935" box="[635,1025,1400,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Pygophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trimaculata">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFD8CEB1AFC189AA6" box="[635,898,1400,1425]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Pygophora trimaculata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="364E4B37313FFF8EFC7EEB1AFB9B9AA6" box="[905,1025,1400,1425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" refId="ref7974" refString="Karl, O. (1935) Aussereuropaische Musciden (Anthomyiden) aus dem Deutschen Entomologischen Institut. Arbeiten uber morphologische und taxonomische Entomologie aus. Berlin-Dahlem, 2, 29 - 49." type="journal article">Karl, 1935</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from Iriomotejima Is. We examined the specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="95DF4D45313FFF8EFE92EBFFFD9D9A82" authorityName="Karl" authorityYear="1935" box="[357,519,1436,1461]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Pygophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trimaculata">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFE92EBFFFD9D9A82" box="[357,519,1436,1461]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">P. trimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
identified by Dr. Shinonaga, which are deposited in EUM. However, they are identified as 
<taxonomicName id="95DF4D45313FFF8EFED0EBA3FE599AEE" baseAuthorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityYear="1918" box="[295,451,1472,1497]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Pygophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicornis">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFED0EBA3FE599AEE" box="[295,451,1472,1497]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">P. longicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and therefore the record of 
<taxonomicName id="95DF4D45313FFF8EFD0CEBA3FC039AEE" authorityName="Karl" authorityYear="1935" box="[763,921,1472,1497]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Pygophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trimaculata">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFD0CEBA3FC039AEE" box="[763,921,1472,1497]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">P. trimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="2AC87656313FFF8EFC2AEBA3FB879AEF" box="[989,1053,1473,1496]" name="Japan" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">Japan</collectingCountry>
is incorrect.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="526036C6313FFF8EFF30EB86FA8A9972" blockId="1.[151,1436,389,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">
Within this genus, there are few differences between the females. In particular, the abdominal characters (terminalia) are very similar as mentioned in the redescriptions below. Therefore, it is very difficult to distinguish closely related species such as 
<taxonomicName id="95DF4D45313FFF8EFE06E84FFD1E9972" box="[497,644,1580,1605]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Pygophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boninensis">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFE06E84FFD1E9972" box="[497,644,1580,1605]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">P. boninensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="95DF4D45313FFF8EFD4DE84FFCDC9972" baseAuthorityName="Wiedemann" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[698,838,1580,1605]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Pygophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="450" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macularis">
<emphasis id="60ABEAD4313FFF8EFD4DE84FFCDC9972" box="[698,838,1580,1605]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="450">P. macularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the female morphological characters.
</paragraph>
